[[ ## reasoning ## ]]
To generate a testbench that passes only the correct mutant of a binary-to-Gray code converter, we need to follow the provided simulation rules and knowledge base. The correct mutant should pass all the checks in the testbench, while any incorrect implementation should fail at least one check. We will create a comprehensive testbench that exercises all bit positions of the input and ensures that the output matches the expected Gray code.

[[ ## testbench_code ## ]]
```verilog
module testbench;

  // Signals
  reg [9:0] bin;
  wire [9:0] gray;

  // Instantiate the DUT
  enc_bin2gray dut (.bin(bin), .gray(gray));

  // Testbench logic
  initial begin
    // Initialize signals
    bin = 10'b0;

    // Loop through all possible input values
    for (integer i = 0; i < 2**10; i = i + 1) begin
      bin = i;
      #10; // Delay to allow signal propagation

      // Calculate the expected Gray code
      reg [9:0] expected_gray;
      expected_gray = bin ^ (bin >> 1);

      // Check if the output matches the expected Gray code
      if (gray !== expected_gray) begin
        $display("TEST FAILED");
        $finish;
      end
    end

    // All tests passed
    $display("TEST PASSED");
    $finish;
  end

endmodule
```

